<br>
I cannot put my ex-husband on my health insurance, even though we are cohabitating and reunited.  Straights cannot  put lovers on health insurance.  Gays also, should not be allowed to put their lovers on their health insurance as this would be a special right they were fighting for, that if they won, would get what straights could not.  All couples, traditional gender or non-traditional, should all have the same, equal rules.  <br>
<br>
Besides, legal marriage is a contract to cohabitate made by man, and therefore, should be available to all who wish to cohabitate.  Religious marriage, on the other hand, to me, is something in the heart, in the ceremony, in the celebration...not in the signing of &quot;do you promise to allow yourself to become a tax-deduction for him and put him on your health insurance, until divorce.&quot;<br>
<br>
Without legal marraige, many gays are having at least the ceremony of &quot;Union&quot;, and I think that's the way my ex and I, though straight,  are going to go with our being reunited.  The marriage penalty with IRS kills us, and well, it's more fun being a live-in mistress than a wife.   <p><!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
